quran[7]{c,v,t}:
  24,1,"A surah{1}that We have sent down and <span class="h">ordained{2}</span>and sent down in it evident signs{3}, that you may <span class="h">remind yourselves{4}</span>.",footnotes:1:[Each portion of the Qur'an is called a ‘surah’, which is sometimes translated as ‘chapter’.],footnotes:2:[<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir and Abu Amr read it as: “…and did ordain…”</span>],footnotes:3:[The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.],footnotes:4:[<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…that you may constantly remember.”</span>]
  24,2,"The fornicating woman and the fornicating man—whip each one of them a hundred lashes and let no compassion towards them keep you<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a>from carrying out Allah’s religion, if you<i class=""s"">(truly) </i>believe in Allah and the Last Day, and let their punishment be witnessed by a group{1}of believers.",footnotes:1:The Arabic word used is the same as that translated as ‘faction’.
  24,3,"The fornicating man marries none but a fornicating woman or an idolatress, and the fornicating woman marries none but a fornicating man or an idolater, and that has been prohibited for the believers."
  24,4,"And those who accuse chaste women then cannot bring four witnesses—whip<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a>them eighty lashes and do not ever accept their testimony, for those are the defiantly disobedient—"
  24,5,"except for those who have repented afterwards and reformed, for indeed, Allah is Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  24,6,"And those who accuse their own spouses but have no witnesses except themselves, then <span class="h">let the testimony of one of them be four oaths{1}</span>by Allah that he is surely of the truthful.",footnotes:1:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…then the testimony of one of them (is binding)—four oaths by Allah…”</span>
  24,7,"And the fifth is: <span class="h">may{1}</span><span class=""h"">Allah’s curse indeed</span><span class=""h"">be</span>upon him if he is of the liars.",footnotes:1:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’ and Ya’qub read it as: “...may Allah’s curse be upon him…”</span>
  24,8,"But what averts punishment from her is that she testifies under oath four times by Allah that he is surely of the liars,"
  24,9,"<span class="h">while{1}</span><span class=""h"">the fifth is: may Allah’s wrath indeed be</span>upon her if he is of the truthful.",footnotes:1:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Nafie’, Ya’qub and Hafs read it as: “…liars. <sub><small>9</small></sub>9 And the fifth is: may Allah’s wrath indeed be upon her…. ” Nafie’ read it as: “...liars. <sub><small>9</small></sub>9 And the fifth is that Allah’s wrath will have fallen upon her...” Ya’qub read it as: “…liars. <sub><small>9</small></sub>9 And the fifth is: may Allah’s wrath be upon her…”</span>
  24,10,"And were it not for Allah’s grace upon you<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a><i class=""s"">, </i>and His mercy, and that Allah is the Granter and Accepter of repentance, All-Wise. . .{1}",footnotes:1:According to most exegetes, this sentence is left open-ended in order to magnify the predicate and leave it to the reader's imagination.
